This paper deals with the problem of inferring the reward function of an agent of unknown rationality, which is a core problem in artificial intelligence. The paper discusses the limitations of Occam's razor in solving this problem, which suggests that the paper is likely to be categorized under cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also discusses the implications of the No Free Lunch theorem, which is a fundamental result in optimization theory, suggesting that the paper may also be categorized under cs.RO (Robotics) and cs.CR (Cryptography and Security). Finally, the paper discusses the need for normative assumptions, which suggests that the paper may also be categorized under cs.SY (Systems and Control).
